  "why": "PAIR is explicitly designed to produce semantic, human-interpretable (i.e., realistic) prompt-level jailbreaks and it preserves the overall attack objective O across iterations (so mutations remain semantically tied to the same goal). The attacker LLM produces natural-language refinements and uses in-context examples and chain-of-thought style ‘improvement’ assessments to keep successive prompts meaningful and plausible. However, PAIR does not impose explicit constraints that preserve similarity to the original seed prompt (e.g., fixing semantically critical content or measuring similarity relative to the original seed) or otherwise prevent cumulative drift across iterations; instead it instructs the attacker to propose changes (even to obfuscate or replace sensitive terms) and relies on short depths (e.g., K=3) and truncated history as pragmatic mitigations. These design choices correspond to enforcing semantic consistency and naturalness primarily between successive mutation steps rather than enforcing preservation relative to the original seed or bounding cumulative distortion, which matches the “Medium” definition.",
